08/12/2004
SOFIA, Bulgaria -- Wrapping up a two-day meeting in Sofia on Tuesday (7 December), the foreign ministers of the OSCE member states vowed to intensify counterterrorism efforts and reaffirmed their commitment to protecting human rights. 
At the end of the event, the current OSCE chairman-in-office, Bulgarian Foreign Minister Solomon Passy, reiterated that the organisation is vital to guaranteeing security and stability.
In other news Tuesday, Moscow announced that the Black Sea Economic Co-operation organisation members would start exchanging anti-terrorist information. 
A protocol drafted by Russia calls for the countries to exchange data on groups and individuals, in order to prevent terrorist attacks. 
(OSCE Web site, Nova TV, Interfax - 07/12/04)
